<p>The old Manila day is one of the easier plans to put together in the country. Intramuros and Binondo sit on opposite banks of the Pasig, both reachable by LRT or jeepney, and the walking distance between the two is short enough that you do not need a car. The trick is timing the morning in the walled city before the sun gets harsh, then crossing over to Binondo for a long lunchtime food walk.</p>
<p>Tara, here is the practical kwento.</p>
<h2>Morning in Intramuros</h2>
<p>Start at Fort Santiago by around 8:30 a.m. The gate opens early and the morning light makes the bahay-na-bato walls look the way the old postcards remember them. Pay the entrance fee at the gate, walk through the Rizal Shrine, then take the river-facing rampart for the slow view over the Pasig.</p>
<h3>Walking the Walled City</h3>
<p>From Fort Santiago, walk south along General Luna Street. The route passes Plaza Roma, Manila Cathedral, and the San Agustin Church and Museum. San Agustin is the oldest stone church in the country and the small museum behind it holds the better Filipino religious art collection. Pay the museum fee, it is worth the slow hour.</p>
<h3>Casa Manila</h3>
<p>Across the street from San Agustin is Casa Manila, the reconstructed Spanish-era house museum. The rooms are arranged the way an upper-class Manila family would have lived in the 1800s, with the entresuelo for the staff and the caida sala on the second floor. Photos are allowed in some rooms, not all, so read the signs at the door.</p>
<h2>Crossing to Binondo</h2>
<p>From Plaza San Luis, walk back north toward the Postigo Gate, then cross Jones Bridge to Binondo. The walk takes around 15 minutes and you pass the old post office building on the river bank. Binondo is the oldest Chinatown in the world, founded in 1594, and the streets still keep that mix of dim-sum kitchens, herbalists, and old hardware stores.</p>
<h3>Where to Start the Food Walk</h3>
<p>Start at Binondo Church on Plaza Calderon de la Barca. From the church plaza, the food trail unspools naturally. Walk down Ongpin Street for the older hawker stalls, then loop back through Quintin Paredes Road for the sit-down places.</p>
<h2>What to Eat</h2>
<ul><li>Kuchay dumplings and hakaw at Wai Ying or Dong Bei Dumpling, the two reliable steamer kitchens</li><li>Pancit Estacion at Ying Ying for the wok-charred Hokkien noodles</li><li>Lechon Macau at Sincerity Cafe, the skin is the point</li><li>Beef ho-fan or wonton mami at Masuki, the old institution near Ongpin</li><li>Hopia and tikoy from Eng Bee Tin for pasalubong on the way out</li></ul>
<p>Eat in small portions across three or four kitchens instead of one big lunch. The Binondo style of eating is sampling, not feasting.</p>
<h3>One Carinderia Worth Finding</h3>
<p>Tucked behind Sincerity Cafe is a smaller carinderia run by the same family, with the same lechon but a lower price and a shorter queue. Ask the staff at the main branch, they will point you to it.</p>
<h2>Coffee and the Closing Walk</h2>
<p>Finish at one of the cafes along Escolta on the way back. Escolta was the main shopping street of Manila in the 1930s and the art-deco buildings still stand. The First United Building and the Calvo Building have small cafes and design studios on the ground floors. Sit out the afternoon heat with a cold brew before heading back to your hotel.</p>
<h2>Getting In and Around</h2>
<p>The easiest way to reach Intramuros is by Grab from any Metro Manila hotel. The LRT-1 stops at Central Terminal which is a 15-minute walk from Fort Santiago. For comparing Manila hotels close to Intramuros and Binondo, you can browse listings on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g298573-Manila_Metro_Manila_Luzon-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<ul><li>A small umbrella for the midday sun or the surprise afternoon rain</li><li>Comfortable shoes, you will walk five to seven kilometers across the day</li><li>Small bills for the food stalls and the jeepney</li><li>A reusable water bottle, the cafes will refill</li><li>A camera with a wide lens, the walls and the church interiors reward it</li></ul>
<p>One full day in old Manila done on foot, with a long lunch in the middle. This is the kind of city day that holds up the second and third visit.</p>
