        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Mt Batulao sits at the Cavite-Batangas border, just past the Tagaytay ridge, and it is the day hike most Manila trekkers start with. The mountain is 811 meters, an inactive volcano with a long open ridge and a string of small campsites along the way. The new trail is the gentler route and the one I recommend for first-timers, the old trail has a few exposed rock scrambles that catch people off guard.</p>
<p>The trip is doable in one long day from Manila. Wake up at 3 a.m., start the climb by 6 a.m., summit by mid-morning, descend by lunch, back in Manila by sunset. Sulit.</p>
<h2>Getting to the Jump-off</h2>
<p>The jump-off is in Barangay Kaylaway in Nasugbu, Batangas. From Manila, the cleanest route is a bus from Coastal Mall in Pasay or from the JAM Liner terminal in Buendia to Nasugbu, then a tricycle to the registration area at Evercrest. The trip takes around three hours one-way depending on traffic on the Sta. Rosa exit.</p>
<h3>Driving Yourself</h3>
<p>If you are driving, take CAVITEX or the Skyway down to the Sta. Rosa-Tagaytay road. Pass Tagaytay City, descend toward Nasugbu, then watch for the Evercrest Golf Course signs on the right. Park at the registration area, the day fee is small and the parking is secured.</p>
<h2>The New Trail</h2>
<p>The new trail starts gently through open grassland and rolling ridges. The path is well-trodden, with bamboo handrails on the steeper sections and small sari-sari stops along the way. Most groups summit in around three to four hours including breaks.</p>
<h3>Campsite Stops</h3>
<p>The trail passes Camp 1, Camp 2, and Camp 3 along the way. Camp 1 is the first water refill, Camp 2 has the best views back toward Taal Lake, and Camp 3 is the last stop before the assault to the summit. Each camp has a small registration log and a coconut vendor when the season is right.</p>
<h3>The Summit Push</h3>
<p>The last hour from Camp 3 is the steepest. The path narrows along a ridge and you scramble the final section on hand and foot. The summit is small but the 360-degree view of Batangas farmland, Mt Talamitam to the south, and Taal Lake to the east is the payoff.</p>
<h2>Descending the Old Trail</h2>
<p>Most groups go up the new trail and come down the old trail to make a loop. The old trail has two exposed rock scrambles and a long bamboo-handrail descent. Wear shoes with grip, take it slow, and use the handrails. The descent takes around two to three hours back to the registration area.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<ul><li>At least two liters of water, more if you sweat heavy</li><li>Trail food, the small stalls run out by midday</li><li>Sun hat or cap, the ridge has no shade</li><li>Shoes with grip, sneakers slip on the loose dirt</li><li>A light jacket for the early start in cool weather</li><li>Small bills for the camp fees and the tricycle</li><li>Trash bag, pack out what you bring in</li></ul>
<h2>Best Months to Climb</h2>
<p>December to February is the cool dry window with the best visibility. March to May is hot and dusty, but the trail is open. The rainy months from June to October close the trail intermittently for safety. Check the Nasugbu tourism office or the trail registration page on the Mt Batulao Facebook group before booking the trip.</p>
<h2>After the Hike</h2>
<p>Nasugbu has a string of small beachfront places along the western Batangas coast that pair well with a Batulao day. Calayo, Papaya Cove, and Natipuan Cove are the quieter options. For overnight stays in the Nasugbu area, you can compare listings on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g612338-Nasugbu_Batangas_Province_Calabarzon-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>.</p>
<h2>One Tip Most Guides Skip</h2>
<p>Hire a local guide at the registration area even if you have read every trail report. The trail markers shift after heavy rain, and the guides know which scramble to take and which to skip. The guide fee is small and the safety margin is real.</p>
<p>Mt Batulao is the right first mountain for Manila hikers. Train your legs on Batulao, then build up to Mt Maculot, then Pulag. The new trail is patient with you.</p>
