        'excerpt' => 'Burot Beach in Calatagan is the closest no-resort camping spot from Manila where you actually sleep on sand. Here is the DIY plan, the fees, and what to bring.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Burot Beach sits on the western tip of Calatagan, Batangas, around three hours from Manila by car. It is one of the last beaches near the capital that still allows overnight camping right on the sand, with no resort wall in the way and no entrance gate after sunset. The community manages the site through a barangay fee, and the rules keep it that way.</p>
<p>This is the slow weekend plan for barkada or families who want to skip the resort buffet and just sleep next to the water.</p>
<h2>Getting There</h2>
<p>The drive from Manila takes around three hours via the SLEX and STAR Tollway, exit at Lipa, then through Balayan toward Calatagan town. From Calatagan town proper, drive another 20 minutes through the coastal road until you reach the Burot Beach entrance signage in Barangay Sta. Ana.</p>
<h3>By Public Transport</h3>
<p>Take a bus from Buendia or Pasay terminals to Calatagan via the Batangas Pier route. From Calatagan town, hire a tricycle for the 20-minute ride to Burot. The tricycle drivers know the route and you can arrange the pickup for the next day at a fixed time. Bring small bills.</p>
<h2>What the Camping Looks Like</h2>
<p>Burot is a long curving beach with cream sand and shallow water that stretches far out before it gets deep. The shoreline has a thin tree line that gives you natural shade for hammocks and tent setups. No buildings, no resort sound system, just the wind and the boats coming back at sunset.</p>
<h3>The Fee Structure</h3>
<p>Pay the day-use fee at the barangay registration kiosk on the way in. The overnight camping fee is separate and you settle it at the same kiosk. Parking is in a marked area near the entrance, and there is a small caretaker fee for keeping watch on the cars. All the fees are flat and posted on a board.</p>
<h3>Facilities, the Honest Version</h3>
<p>There are basic shared restrooms and a shower stall managed by the barangay. The water is rainwater so plan to bring drinking water from town. There is no electricity at the campsite, no Wi-Fi, no carinderia after dark. Bring everything you need.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<ul><li>A tent or hammock with a tarp, the dew can be heavy near sunrise</li><li>Drinking water, at least three liters per person for the overnight</li><li>A small portable stove and easy meals, no open fires on the sand</li><li>A headlamp or lantern, the camp is dark after sunset</li><li>A trash bag, pack out everything including food scraps</li><li>Insect repellent, the mangroves bring mosquitoes at dusk</li><li>A power bank, no charging on site</li><li>Aqua shoes for the rocky parts on the southern end</li></ul>
<h2>What to Do</h2>
<p>The Burot routine is simple. Swim in the morning when the water is glassy, snorkel near the rocky south end where the small fish school, then sit out the noon heat under the trees. Walk the long beach in the afternoon, eat dinner before sunset, then sleep early because the night gets quiet fast.</p>
<h3>Optional Side Trips</h3>
<p>If you want a daytime add-on, drive 30 minutes to Cape Santiago Lighthouse for the small heritage stop. Or take the boat from the Burot pier for a one-hour island-hop to Sombrero Island for snorkeling.</p>
<h2>Where to Stay if Camping Is Not Your Plan</h2>
<p>If you want a roof and a bed instead of a tent, the Calatagan coast has a string of small beachfront places along Barangay Sta. Ana and Barangay Carlosa. You can compare listings on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g776106-Calatagan_Batangas_Province_Calabarzon-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>.</p>
<h2>The Rules That Keep Burot Burot</h2>
<p>Pack out your trash. No open fires on the sand. No loud sound systems after 10 p.m. Respect the caretakers and the barangay staff. The community keeps the beach open to campers precisely because most travelers follow the rules. The day they stop following the rules is the day a private resort buys the land.</p>
<p>Burot is the read on slow Batangas camping. Three hours from Manila, no resort, just the long beach and the night sky.</p>
