        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Mt Gulugod Baboy is the short ridge that sits above the diving town of Anilao in Mabini, Batangas. The name is local for the curved pig spine the ridge resembles. At 525 meters, it is one of the easier sunrise hikes from Manila, with a wide grassland trail and a long view down to the Maricaban Strait and Verde Island.</p>
<p>The hike pairs naturally with a day of diving or snorkeling in Anilao, which is why most Manila divers do the climb on the first morning of the trip. Tara, here is the plan.</p>
<h2>Getting to the Jump-off</h2>
<p>The jump-off is in Barangay Phil-Asia, near the Philpan Dive Resort road in Anilao. From Manila, drive via SLEX and STAR Tollway, exit at Batangas City, then follow the signs to Mabini and Anilao. The drive takes around three hours without traffic. If you are coming by bus, JAM Liner runs the Cubao to Mabini route, then a tricycle to Phil-Asia.</p>
<h3>The Early Start</h3>
<p>For a sunrise summit, leave Manila by 11 p.m. the night before, or better, drive in the afternoon and sleep at a dive resort in Anilao. Start the hike by 4 a.m. The trail is well-marked but a headlamp is non-negotiable in the dark.</p>
<h2>The Trail</h2>
<p>Register at the Phil-Asia jump-off where a small kiosk collects the trail fee. The path climbs through coconut groves for the first 30 minutes, then opens to grassland and the long ridge. The total climb takes around one and a half to two hours at a relaxed pace.</p>
<h3>The Ridge Walk</h3>
<p>The ridge is the best part of the hike. You walk along the spine of the mountain with a clear view of Verde Island Passage on one side and the Batangas lowland on the other. The grass holds the morning dew and the path is wide enough for groups to walk side by side.</p>
<h3>The Summit</h3>
<p>The summit is a small clearing with a wooden marker. From the top, you see Maricaban Island, Verde Island, and the dive boats already heading out for the morning. On clear days, the silhouette of Mindoro rises across the strait. Sit out the sunrise, drink coffee from your thermos, then start the descent.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<ul><li>A headlamp for the pre-dawn start</li><li>One to two liters of water</li><li>Light snacks, the trail is short so a full meal is not needed</li><li>A windbreaker for the ridge, it gets cool before sunrise</li><li>Shoes with grip, the descent has a few loose-rock sections</li><li>Small bills for the trail fee and the tricycle</li></ul>
<h2>After the Hike</h2>
<p>Descend by 7 a.m., back at the dive resort by 8, then breakfast and a morning dive or snorkel. Anilao is the macro diving capital of the country, with the best small-life sites on the Maricaban side of the strait. If you do not dive, snorkel off the house reef of any of the dive resorts along the Anilao coast.</p>
<h3>The Side Trip Option</h3>
<p>From the Anilao pier, you can boat across to Sombrero Island or Sepok Wall for a half-day snorkeling trip. The boatmen quote per banca for the day, and the price is reasonable when split across a barkada.</p>
<h2>Where to Stay</h2>
<p>Anilao is built around diving, so most accommodations are dive resorts with full board. For the wider range of options including non-diver stays, you can compare listings on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g6841596-Anilao_Mabini_Batangas_Province_Calabarzon-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>. Stay along the Phil-Asia road if you want quick trail access. Stay near Solo Sunset Cove if you want the better beach swim.</p>
<h2>Best Months to Climb</h2>
<p>November to April is the dry window with clear summit views. The trail is open year-round but the rainy months from June to September make the grass slippery and the view fogged in. Avoid the climb on weekends if you want the ridge to yourself, the trail gets crowded with Manila day-trippers.</p>
<p>Gulugod Baboy is the right warm-up hike if you are building toward bigger peaks. Two hours up, a long view at the top, then breakfast back in Anilao. This is the calm Batangas weekend.</p>
