        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Pandi is the quiet Bulacan town one hour north of Manila that most travelers drive past on the way to somewhere else. Tate Haus is a small farm staycation in Pandi that has been picking up steam with families and barkada groups looking for a calm weekend without committing to the long Tagaytay drive. The setup is simple, a private house surrounded by rice fields, a small pool, and the kind of farm meals you remember.</p>
<p>This is the kwento for a slow Bulacan weekend that fits into one tank of gas.</p>
<h2>Getting There</h2>
<p>From Manila, the drive takes around one and a half hours via NLEX, exit at Marilao or Sta. Maria, then through the secondary roads to Pandi proper. The last 10 minutes is along a narrow farm road, and the gate is marked with a small wooden sign. Most ride-share apps know the address but the signal drops in the last stretch, so screenshot the map before you leave.</p>
<h3>By Public Transport</h3>
<p>Take a bus from Cubao or Caloocan terminals bound for Pandi or Sta. Maria. From the Pandi market, hire a tricycle for the short ride to the farm. The driver will know the area if you say Tate Haus by name.</p>
<h2>What the Place Looks Like</h2>
<p>The main house is a converted family home with three bedrooms, a long living-dining area, and a kitchen that fits a group cooking together. The front lanai opens to a small pool surrounded by a fenced lawn. Beyond the fence, the rice fields stretch to the tree line.</p>
<h3>The Pool and Lanai</h3>
<p>The pool is family-sized, not lap-sized, which suits the slow morning swim and the afternoon float more than a workout. The lanai has long shared tables, a barbecue grill, and a small bar counter. Most groups eat outside because the breeze through the fields keeps the place cool even in summer.</p>
<h3>The Farm Activities</h3>
<p>The hosts arrange optional farm activities for families, including a short farm walk to the rice paddies, fruit-picking when in season, and a small visit to the chicken coop and the goat pen for the kids. Nothing rushed, all optional, and most of it is included in the booking.</p>
<h2>What to Pack</h2>
<ul><li>Light cotton clothes, the field heat is real even in the cool months</li><li>Insect repellent, the mosquitoes find you at dusk</li><li>A speaker if your barkada wants music, the place is private enough</li><li>Groceries from town if you plan to cook, the nearest big market is in Sta. Maria</li><li>Slippers, the lanai floor and the pool deck are barefoot-friendly</li><li>A power bank, the Wi-Fi is decent but the signal in the bedrooms is patchy</li></ul>
<h2>What to Eat</h2>
<p>The hosts can arrange a basic Filipino breakfast spread on request, with longganisa, garlic rice, and eggs. For lunch and dinner, most groups bring their own groceries and cook on the grill, or order in from one of the carinderias along the Pandi main road. Try the inihaw na liempo from the small grill stall near the Pandi market, ask the caretaker to point you to it.</p>
<h2>Side Trips from Pandi</h2>
<p>If you want a half-day side trip, drive 30 minutes to Biak-na-Bato National Park in San Miguel for the cave system and the river hike. Or drive 45 minutes to the Plaridel Airfield for the small aviation museum. Most groups skip these and just stay put at the farm, which is honestly the right call.</p>
<h2>Booking Notes</h2>
<p>Tate Haus is booked through their Facebook page and direct messaging. The weekend slots fill up two to three months ahead in the cool dry season. Weekday slots are easier and often quieter. For broader Bulacan accommodation options near Pandi, you can compare listings on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g4067354-Bulacan_Province_Central_Luzon-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>.</p>
<h2>One Tip Most Visitors Skip</h2>
<p>Ask the caretaker about the small chapel on the property. The hosts built a quiet open-air chapel at the back of the lot, near the fields, and it is a calm spot for an early morning sit before the rest of the group wakes up. Coffee and the field sounds, then breakfast.</p>
<p>Pandi is the Bulacan weekend that proves you do not need to drive three hours for a real break. Tate Haus is one of the easier slow-weekend stays north of Manila.</p>
