        'excerpt' => 'Camaya Coast in Mariveles is the ferry-accessed beach community three hours from Manila that suits a calm weekend without the long drive around Bataan.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Camaya Coast sits on the Mariveles side of Bataan, on the western coast facing Corregidor and the open South China Sea. The community is reached by a passenger ferry from the Esplanade Seaside Terminal in Pasay, which makes it the easiest Bataan weekend if you do not want to drive the long loop around Manila Bay and across the bridge.</p>
<p>This is the calm read for a weekend at Camaya, ferry first, beach second, and the slow afternoons that come with both.</p>
<h2>Getting There by Ferry</h2>
<p>The ferry leaves from the Esplanade Seaside Terminal in Pasay, near the Mall of Asia complex. The schedule runs roughly two to three times a day, with the morning departure being the most reliable. Book ahead through the Camaya Coast website or the SeaJet ticket counter at the terminal. The crossing takes around one hour each way, depending on sea conditions.</p>
<h3>The Drive Option</h3>
<p>If the ferry sells out, the drive from Manila takes around three to four hours via NLEX, SCTEX, and the Bataan Provincial Road. The drive is straightforward but long, and the last stretch into Mariveles passes through industrial port areas before opening to the coast. Most weekenders choose the ferry for the time saved.</p>
<h2>What the Beach Looks Like</h2>
<p>Camaya Coast has a long stretch of golden sand that curves around a sheltered bay. The water is calm most of the year because the bay faces inward toward Corregidor, blocking the open swells. The sand is finer than the typical Bataan beach, almost cream-colored, with a gentle drop-off into the swimming area.</p>
<h3>The Beach Facilities</h3>
<p>The beachfront has shared lounge areas, kayak rentals, and a small water sports counter for paddle boards and banana boats. There is a beachfront cafe and a few casual restaurants along the boardwalk. The setup leans family-friendly, with lifeguards on duty during day hours.</p>
<h3>The Pool Complex</h3>
<p>The pool complex is separate from the beach and faces the same bay. The infinity edge looks out toward Corregidor on a clear day. Most families split time between the pool in the morning and the beach in the afternoon.</p>
<h2>What to Do Beyond the Beach</h2>
<ul><li>Kayak the calm bay in the early morning before the wind picks up</li><li>Walk the boardwalk to the small mangrove area at the north end</li><li>Snorkel near the rocky south point, basic gear is rented at the beach kiosk</li><li>Sunset photos at the western viewpoint, the light over the strait is the best part of the day</li><li>Stargazing on the beach, the light pollution is low</li></ul>
<h2>Side Trips from Camaya</h2>
<p>A short ferry hop from the Camaya pier takes you across to Corregidor Island for the World War II heritage tour. The day tour covers Malinta Tunnel, the Mile-Long Barracks, and the Pacific War Memorial. Book the Corregidor side trip in advance because it runs on a fixed schedule.</p>
<h3>Las Casas Filipinas</h3>
<p>From Mariveles, you can drive 45 minutes north to Bagac for Las Casas Filipinas de Acuzar, the heritage park of relocated bahay-na-bato houses. This pairs naturally as a half-day stop on the way back if you are driving instead of taking the ferry.</p>
<h2>Where to Stay</h2>
<p>Camaya Coast itself has a range of accommodations from beachfront condotels to family villas, all within the gated community and accessible only to guests. For the wider Mariveles and Bataan accommodation options, you can compare listings on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g672912-Bataan_Province_Central_Luzon-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<ul><li>Reef-safe sunscreen and a hat</li><li>Aqua shoes for the rocky south end of the beach</li><li>A light jacket for the early morning kayak</li><li>Small bills for the boardwalk vendors</li><li>A power bank, the ferry terminal Wi-Fi is patchy</li><li>Your booking confirmation, the gate staff check before letting you in</li></ul>
<h2>Best Months to Visit</h2>
<p>November to May is the dry window with the calmest sea. June to October brings the southwest habagat with stronger waves and the occasional ferry cancellation, so check with the operator before booking the trip. The cool dry months from December to February are the best for the long beach walks.</p>
<p>Camaya Coast is the read on a Bataan weekend that skips the long drive. Ferry across, sit on the beach for two nights, and let the bay do the work.</p>
