    [
        'source_url' => 'https://twomonkeystravelgroup.com/travel-from-manila-to-baguio/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Two Monkeys Travel Group',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Manila to Baguio: An Honest Read on the Bus Routes',
        'slug' => 'manila-to-baguio-bus-routes-honest-read',
        'excerpt' => 'The Manila to Baguio bus trip has more options now than first-time travelers realize. Here is the honest comparison of operators, terminals, and route picks.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Baguio is the easiest mountain trip from Manila and the bus route is the most common way to get there. The drive is around six hours via TPLEX and the Marcos Highway, or seven hours via the older Kennon Road when that route is open. The bus operators are mostly reliable, but the terminal pick and the schedule choice matter more than most travelers realize.</p>
<p>This is the practical comparison for first-timers and returning travelers picking a route to Baguio.</p>
<h2>The Main Operators</h2>
<p>Three operators run the Manila to Baguio route consistently. Victory Liner has the largest fleet and the most departures. Genesis Transport runs the premium Joybus First Class line with reclining sleeper seats. Solid North runs the budget overnight option.</p>
<h3>Victory Liner</h3>
<p>Victory Liner has terminals in Cubao, Pasay, Caloocan, and Sampaloc. The Cubao terminal is the busiest and has the most departures across the day. The standard air-conditioned bus is the workhorse fleet. The Deluxe and First Class buses have wider seats and fewer stops. Travel time is around six to seven hours.</p>
<h3>Genesis Joybus First Class</h3>
<p>Genesis runs the Joybus First Class from the Cubao Bus Station and from the Pasay Avenida terminal. This is the only sleeper-seat option with the seat that reclines nearly flat, blanket and pillow included, and a snack pack at boarding. The route uses TPLEX and Marcos Highway only, no Kennon detour. Travel time is around five to six hours.</p>
<h3>Solid North</h3>
<p>Solid North runs the cheaper overnight bus from the Cubao terminal. The fleet is older but the seats are functional. The overnight schedule means you arrive in Baguio around dawn, which is sulit if you are trying to maximize the trip days.</p>
<h2>Which Route to Pick</h2>
<p>The TPLEX route is the default. It exits NLEX at Hermosa, runs through Tarlac and Pangasinan, then turns onto Marcos Highway for the climb into the city. The drive is mostly highway with minimal sharp turns, which makes it the friendlier route if you get motion sickness.</p>
<h3>Kennon Road, When Open</h3>
<p>Kennon Road is the older route, with sharper switchbacks and the famous Lion's Head landmark at the entrance. The drive is shorter in distance but slower because of the turns, and it closes intermittently during the rainy season due to landslides. Check the DPWH advisories or the Victory Liner customer hotline before booking the trip if you want Kennon.</p>
<h2>Booking Tips</h2>
<ul><li>Book in advance for long weekends and the Panagbenga month of February</li><li>Online booking through the operator websites or Pinoy Travel app is the easiest</li><li>Pick the morning departure if it is your first time, so you arrive while the city is awake</li><li>Pick the overnight bus if you have a tight trip schedule</li><li>Avoid the bus departures on Friday afternoons, the EDSA traffic adds two hours</li></ul>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<ul><li>A jacket or hoodie, the bus aircon is aggressive and Baguio is cold on arrival</li><li>A neck pillow for the overnight buses</li><li>Snacks and water, the rest stops have small meals but limited choices</li><li>A power bank, the USB ports on the older buses are unreliable</li><li>Motion sickness tablets if the Marcos Highway turns get to you</li><li>A small bag with valuables for the seat with you, the luggage hold is for bigger bags</li></ul>
<h2>Driving Instead</h2>
<p>If you are driving, take NLEX, SCTEX, and TPLEX. Exit at Rosario in La Union, then climb Marcos Highway to Baguio. Toll fees add up. Parking in Baguio is limited and expensive in the city center, so most drivers park at SM Baguio or at the hotel and walk into Session Road.</p>
<h2>Other Options</h2>
<p>A handful of small private van operators run the route from Cubao and Pasay, with door-to-door drop-off at Baguio hotels for a premium. Useful if you are with a small group and want a faster transfer.</p>
<h2>After You Arrive</h2>
<p>Baguio has a long list of cool-weather accommodations from heritage inns near Session Road to quieter places near Camp John Hay. For the wider range, you can compare options on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g469394-Baguio_Benguet_Province_Cordillera_Region_Luzon-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>. Stay near Session Road for the walkable food and shopping. Stay near Camp John Hay for the calmer pine-side mornings.</p>
<p>The bus to Baguio is the easy trip if you book ahead and pick the right departure. Six hours up, the cool air on arrival, and the city does the rest.</p>
