    [
        'source_url' => 'https://twomonkeystravelgroup.com/itinerary-cebu-bohol/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Two Monkeys Travel Group',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Cebu and Bohol: A Ten Day Multi-Island Loop',
        'slug' => 'cebu-bohol-ten-day-multi-island-loop-itinerary',
        'excerpt' => 'A patient ten day plan that pairs Cebu and Bohol with a side hop to Siquijor or Camiguin. Here is the route, the ferry connections, and how to pace it.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Cebu and Bohol are the two most accessible Central Visayas islands, both with direct international flights and fast ferry links between them. A ten-day loop that pairs the two, with one side hop to either Siquijor or Camiguin, is one of the better paced multi-island plans in the country. Long enough to slow down, short enough to feel like a real trip.</p>
<p>This is the calm read for a ten-day route across Cebu, Bohol, and one side island.</p>
<h2>The Route</h2>
<p>Fly into Cebu, base in Cebu City for two nights, then go south to Moalboal for two nights, ferry to Tagbilaran, base in Panglao Bohol for three nights with countryside day trips, then ferry to either Siquijor for three nights or back to Cebu and onward to Camiguin. Fly out from your last island.</p>
<h2>Days 1 to 2: Cebu City</h2>
<p>Land at Mactan-Cebu International, cross to Cebu City for the historic stops. Magellan's Cross, the Basilica del Santo Nino, Fort San Pedro, and the heritage walk through Calle Colon. Eat lechon at the local institutions in Talisay or in Punta Princesa, then end the second day with a coffee at one of the cafes in the IT Park area.</p>
<h3>Where to Eat in Cebu City</h3>
<p>For lechon, try the smaller stalls in Talisay over the famous chains. The skin-to-meat ratio is better and the price is fair. For breakfast, find a puso stand and pair the hanging rice with a grilled chicken inasal. For coffee, the cafes around Crossroads Mall and IT Park are the reliable picks.</p>
<h2>Days 3 to 4: Moalboal</h2>
<p>From Cebu City, take a van or bus to Moalboal in southwest Cebu. The drive takes around three hours through the inland route. Base in Panagsama Beach for the easy snorkel access. The headline activity is the sardine run, a year-round school of millions of sardines that swirls just off the shore.</p>
<h3>Side Trip to Kawasan</h3>
<p>From Moalboal, take a 30-minute van to Badian for the Kawasan Falls. The lower falls are accessible by a short forest hike from the parking area. Swim in the turquoise pool, eat lunch at the small bamboo cafes, then head back to Moalboal for the afternoon snorkel.</p>
<h2>Days 5 to 7: Bohol</h2>
<p>From Moalboal, take a van back to Cebu City or to Argao for the ferry to Tagbilaran. The Argao to Tagbilaran route is shorter than the Cebu City route and the ferries are smaller. From Tagbilaran, transfer to Panglao for the beach base. Three nights in Panglao is the right length for the Bohol stops.</p>
<h3>The Countryside Day Tour</h3>
<p>The standard Bohol countryside tour covers the Chocolate Hills, the Loboc River cruise, the Tarsier Sanctuary, the Blood Compact site, and the Baclayon Church. Book a private van rather than the group tour if you can, the pace is better and you can skip the stops that do not interest you.</p>
<h3>The Beach and the Reef</h3>
<p>Day two in Panglao is for the beach and the reef. Snorkel at Alona, swim off Doljo, or take the early morning island hopping tour to Balicasag for the proper coral and the chance to see sea turtles. Book the tour through your accommodation or directly at the Alona pier.</p>
<h2>Days 8 to 10: Siquijor</h2>
<p>From Tagbilaran, the OceanJet fast ferry to Siquijor takes around two hours. Base in San Juan for the western beach access and the sunset crowd. Three nights is the right pace for the island scooter loop, the Cambugahay Falls swim, the Salagdoong Beach day, and the Lazi heritage church visit.</p>
<h3>The Scooter Loop</h3>
<p>Rent a scooter from your accommodation and ride the perimeter road. The full loop is around 80 kilometers and takes a relaxed day with stops. Helmet, sun cream, and a small water bottle are the essentials. The road is paved and well-marked, and the scooter rental day rate is reasonable.</p>
<h2>The Alternate Side Hop, Camiguin</h2>
<p>Instead of Siquijor, you can fly from Cebu to Camiguin via the small daily flight, or take the longer ferry route through Cagayan de Oro. Camiguin has a different feel, more volcanic and quieter, with the White Island sandbar and the Sunken Cemetery as the headline stops. Three nights here works the same way as Siquijor.</p>
<h2>Where to Stay</h2>
<p>Each leg has its own accommodation pattern. Cebu City has the full range from heritage to modern. Moalboal is dive-resort centric. Panglao has both beachfront and inland options. Siquijor and Camiguin lean smaller and more local. For the wider range, you can compare across cities on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g294253-Philippines-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>.</p>
<h2>Getting Around Tips</h2>
<ul><li>Book the inter-island ferry tickets in advance through OceanJet or 2GO during peak season</li><li>Plan one buffer day in case a ferry is canceled due to weather</li><li>Carry small bills for the tricycles, jeepneys, and the small entrance fees</li><li>Download offline maps before each leg, the signal drops in the southern Cebu route and on Siquijor</li><li>Pack light, the boat transfers and the scooter rentals all favor a single backpack</li></ul>
<p>Ten days, three islands, and the slow rhythm that only a multi-island loop in the Visayas can deliver. The route holds up on first visit and on the return trip.</p>
