        'source_url' => 'https://twomonkeystravelgroup.com/best-surfing-spots-philippines/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Two Monkeys Travel Group',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Best Surfing Spots in the Philippines: A Calm Roundup',
        'slug' => 'best-surfing-spots-philippines-calm-roundup',
        'excerpt' => 'The country has more surfing than first-timers realize. Here is a calm read on the main breaks across La Union, Siargao, Baler, Catanduanes, and the lesser stops.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>The Philippines has surf year-round if you know which coast to be on. The northeast monsoon from October to March powers the eastern breaks of Siargao, Catanduanes, and Baler. The southwest habagat from June to October powers the western breaks of La Union and parts of Zambales. The shoulder months in between are the friendliest for first-timers.</p>
<p>This is the calm read on the main surfing stops, with the breaks, the seasons, and what each suits.</p>
<h2>La Union, The First Mountain for Most</h2>
<p>La Union sits on the northwest Luzon coast and the surf town of San Juan is the closest real break to Manila. The wave at Urbiztondo Beach is mostly a reef break with sand bottom, friendly enough for beginners during the small swell months and challenging enough for intermediates when the habagat picks up.</p>
<h3>Best Months at La Union</h3>
<p>July to October is the prime habagat season with consistent overhead waves. April to June is the shoulder, with smaller waves suited to learners. The town has a long row of surf schools along the beach, and the rental for boards and lessons is standardized.</p>
<h2>Siargao, The Country's Surf Capital</h2>
<p>Siargao in Surigao del Norte holds the title for the country's surfing capital, and Cloud 9 is the named reef break that hosts the international competitions. The wave is fast, hollow, and breaks over a shallow reef, which makes Cloud 9 itself a spot for experienced surfers rather than first-timers.</p>
<h3>Beginner Options on Siargao</h3>
<p>Quiksilver, Jacking Horse, and Sunday Beach all have gentler breaks suited to beginners and intermediates. Most surf schools in General Luna town offer lessons at these spots before progressing students to Cloud 9. The wave window runs strongest from September to early December, with the off-season from April to June good for learning.</p>
<h2>Baler, The Aurora Coast</h2>
<p>Baler in Aurora is the second most common surf destination from Manila, around five to six hours by bus. Sabang Beach is the long sand-bottom break and the main learner area. Cemento Reef on the other end of the bay is for experienced surfers when the swell is up. The town is small, walkable, and the surf school scene is well-developed.</p>
<h3>Best Months at Baler</h3>
<p>October to March is the prime season for Baler, with consistent waves and cool weather. The summer months are flat but the town stays open for the lesson business and the inland excursions.</p>
<h2>Catanduanes, The Patient Trip</h2>
<p>Puraran Beach on the eastern coast of Catanduanes has the Majestics break, a long right-hand reef break that draws serious surfers from across Southeast Asia during the typhoon swell season. The island requires a flight to Virac and a transfer to Baras town, which is why Catanduanes stays quieter than Siargao or La Union.</p>
<h3>Who Catanduanes Suits</h3>
<p>This is not a beginner spot. The wave is fast and the reef is shallow. But for intermediate to advanced surfers looking for a quieter break with the same swell quality as Cloud 9, Catanduanes is the patient pick. Best months are September to November.</p>
<h2>San Fernando City, La Union Northern Stretch</h2>
<p>Beyond the well-known Urbiztondo break, the northern stretch of La Union has lesser-known spots like Mona Lisa Point and Carille that suit surfers looking for less crowded waves. These spots require a scooter ride from San Juan and the local surf community can point you in the right direction.</p>
<h2>Zambales, The Liwliwa Side</h2>
<p>Liwliwa in San Felipe, Zambales is the closest beach-break alternative to La Union for Manila surfers. The drive is around four hours via SCTEX. The break is sand-bottom and friendlier than the reef breaks elsewhere, making it a fair learner option during the habagat months from July to October.</p>
<h2>Lanuza, The Mindanao Stretch</h2>
<p>Lanuza in Surigao del Sur is the lesser-known surf town on the same eastern Mindanao stretch as Siargao. The wave at Doot Poktoy beach picks up during the same swell season but the crowd is a fraction of Siargao's. Good option for travelers who want the Mindanao surf without the General Luna scene.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<ul><li>A rashguard for the long lesson sessions in the sun</li><li>Reef-safe sunscreen, surf zones are sensitive ecosystems</li><li>Aqua shoes for the reef-break entries</li><li>A dry bag for valuables on the beach</li><li>Cash for the small surf school registration fees and the board rentals</li><li>A reusable water bottle, hydration matters more than you think</li></ul>
<h2>Lesson Tips for Beginners</h2>
<p>Take at least three lessons before judging your progress. The first lesson is for learning to pop up, the second is for paddling out and timing the wave, the third is when the form starts to make sense. Pick a surf school with International Surfing Association certified instructors when possible. Stick to one beach for the lesson series so you read the same break across multiple sessions.</p>
<h2>Where to Stay</h2>
<p>Each surf town has its own accommodation pattern. La Union has guesthouses and hostels along the Urbiztondo beach road. Siargao has the wider range from beachfront to inland coconut farm stays. For the wider range across surf towns, you can compare options on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g294253-Philippines-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>.</p>
<p>The country has surf for every level if you read the season and pick the right coast. La Union for the easy start, Siargao for the destination, Baler for the weekend, Catanduanes for the patient trip.</p>
