    [
        'source_url' => 'https://twomonkeystravelgroup.com/things-to-do-dumaguete/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Two Monkeys Travel Group',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Dumaguete Three Day Plan with Twin Lakes and Apo Island',
        'slug' => 'dumaguete-three-day-plan-twin-lakes-apo',
        'excerpt' => 'A patient three day plan that pairs the Dumaguete city walk with Twin Lakes in the highlands and Apo Island for the diving. Here is the route and what to pack.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Dumaguete is the small university city in Negros Oriental that earns its City of Gentle People reputation. The pace is unhurried, the food scene is honest, and the day trips from the city center cover both highland forest and Apo Island marine sanctuary within a short drive. A three-day plan that bases in Dumaguete and rotates between Twin Lakes, Apo, and the city itself is one of the calmer multi-day setups in the Visayas.</p>
<p>Tara, here is the practical kwento.</p>
<h2>Day 1: Settle in Dumaguete</h2>
<p>Fly in to Dumaguete-Sibulan Airport from Manila or Cebu, then take a tricycle to your accommodation in the city. Drop your bags, walk the Rizal Boulevard along the bay, and settle in at one of the small cafes along the waterfront. The promenade is the social heart of the city in the late afternoon, with joggers, students, and the long sit-and-watch crowd.</p>
<h3>What to Eat on the First Night</h3>
<p>Eat sansrival at Sans Rival on Rizal Boulevard, the cake is a local institution. For dinner, try the silvanas at the same shop or head to Lab-as for the fresh seafood with a Visayan menu. End the night with a calamansi juice on the boulevard before turning in early for the highland trip the next day.</p>
<h2>Day 2: Twin Lakes and the Forest Camp</h2>
<p>Hire a tricycle or rent a scooter for the day trip to Twin Lakes National Park, around an hour north of Dumaguete in the foothills of Sibulan. The road climbs through small mountain villages and the temperature drops noticeably as you go up.</p>
<h3>The Two Lakes</h3>
<p>The park is named for Lake Balinsasayao and Lake Danao, two volcanic lakes sitting side by side in the highland forest. Pay the entrance fee at the kiosk, then take the short walk to the viewpoint over Lake Balinsasayao. The water is dark green and still, and the surrounding forest holds the sound in.</p>
<h3>The Optional Hike</h3>
<p>For the more active visit, hire a local guide for the hike to Puncak Tanawan, the ridge between the two lakes that gives the panoramic view. The hike takes around two to three hours round trip and the path is forested but slippery in places. Wear proper shoes.</p>
<h3>Forest Camp on the Way Back</h3>
<p>On the way back to Dumaguete, stop at Forest Camp in Valencia for the natural pools along the Ocoy River. The water is cold mountain runoff and the swim is the best after the long highland day. Sit out the afternoon under the trees before heading back to the city.</p>
<h2>Day 3: Apo Island</h2>
<p>Apo Island is the small volcanic island around an hour south of Dumaguete, off the town of Dauin. The marine sanctuary around the island has one of the longest-running community-managed reefs in the country, with healthy coral, dense fish populations, and a resident sea turtle community that comes close to swimmers.</p>
<h3>Getting to Apo</h3>
<p>Take a tricycle or a van from Dumaguete to Malatapay port in Zamboanguita. From Malatapay, register at the tourism office and board the banca for the 30-minute crossing to Apo. The fees include the boat, the marine sanctuary entrance, and the optional snorkeling gear rental.</p>
<h3>What to Do on Apo</h3>
<p>Snorkel the marine sanctuary along the western beach, swim with the sea turtles in the shallow grazing area, then hike the short trail to the lighthouse for the island view. Lunch at one of the small carinderias on the island, then catch the afternoon banca back to Malatapay.</p>
<h3>The Diving Option</h3>
<p>If you dive, Apo Island has several wall and slope sites that justify a full day rather than a snorkel-only visit. Most dive operators are based in Dauin and run the Apo dive trips on a daily schedule. The black sand slopes off Dauin itself are the macro diving capital of the Visayas, with the rare critters that draw underwater photographers from across the world.</p>
<h2>Optional Add-On: Siquijor</h2>
<p>If you have one extra day, take the OceanJet fast ferry from Dumaguete to Siquijor for a scooter loop around the smaller neighboring island. The ferry takes around 45 minutes one way and the day works as a long day-trip if you start early and return on the late afternoon boat.</p>
<h2>Where to Stay</h2>
<p>Dumaguete has a wide range of accommodations from heritage inns near Silliman University to modern stays near the boulevard. For the wider range, you can compare options on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g729475-Dumaguete_City_Negros_Oriental_Province_Negros_Island_Region-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>. Stay near Rizal Boulevard for the walkable food and the bay view. Stay near Silliman for the quieter university-side mornings.</p>
<h2>What to Pack</h2>
<ul><li>Reef-safe sunscreen for the Apo day, no sprays</li><li>A light long-sleeve for the highland Twin Lakes morning</li><li>Aqua shoes for both Apo and the Forest Camp pools</li><li>A dry bag for the Apo boat ride</li><li>Cash for the entrance fees and the boat fares, no card terminals at Malatapay</li><li>A power bank, the Apo Island has limited charging</li><li>A reusable water bottle, refills at the cafes in Dumaguete</li></ul>
<h2>Best Months to Visit</h2>
<p>November to May is the dry window with the calmest sea for Apo and the best visibility for the diving. The summer months from March to May get hot at sea level but Twin Lakes stays cool. The rainy season from June to October brings the occasional ferry cancellation for Apo, so check the forecast.</p>
<p>Dumaguete is the calm Negros Oriental trip that proves the smaller cities sometimes deliver more than the bigger ones. Three days, one highland, one island, and one city walk.</p>
